d_overall_means.might = format_data(d.might) %>%
  group_by(modal, workerid) %>% 
  summarise(rating_m_overall = mean(rating))

d_overall_means.probably = format_data(d.probably) %>%
  group_by(modal, workerid) %>% 
  summarise(rating_m_overall = mean(rating))


d_indiv_means.might =  format_data(d.might) %>%
  group_by(modal,percentage_blue, workerid) %>% 
  summarise(rating_m = mean(rating))

d_indiv_means.probably =  format_data(d.probably) %>%
  group_by(modal,percentage_blue, workerid) %>% 
  summarise(rating_m = mean(rating))

d_indiv_merged.might = merge(d_indiv_means.might, d_overall_means.might, by=c("workerid", "modal"))

d_indiv_merged.probably = merge(d_indiv_means.probably, d_overall_means.probably, by=c("workerid", "modal"))


cors.might = d_indiv_merged.might %>%
  group_by(workerid) %>%
  summarise(corr = cor(rating_m, rating_m_overall))

cors.probably = d_indiv_merged.probably %>%
  group_by(workerid) %>%
  summarise(corr = cor(rating_m, rating_m_overall))

Aggregated results

AUC computation

Method 1

Here, we fit a linear model with natural cubic splines with 4 degrees of freedom to the might curve and the probably curve. We then, use this model to predict ratings in the interval \(x=[0,100]\) with step size 0.1. Using these points, we use the AUC function with the trapezoid method to compute the AUC. This is very similar to what is done in Yildirim et al. (2015) except that we are using 4 df instead of 2, as this seems to lead to a better model fit (and given that we have 9 observations/participant, this is still not going to overfit).

t-test:
